While building the AI-Assisted Margin and Shipping Exception Monitor, I learned that the project only becomes useful when the data contains real business exceptions to detect.

After joining the orders, costs, and shipments tables and adding the first business calculations, I confirmed three important signals:

Negative margins = orders where the total cost is higher than the selling price, meaning the business is losing money
Low margins = orders that are still profitable, but only slightly, making them financially risky
Positive delay days = shipments delivered after the promised date, meaning they are late

These are good signs for the MVP, because if none of these cases existed, the monitor would have nothing meaningful to flag.

What I learned
A working query is not enough; the joined dataset must also be validated for row count, duplicates, and nulls
LEFT JOIN was the right choice because orders are the main business grain and I wanted to keep all orders even if related data was missing
Business calculations such as margin value, margin percentage, and delay days are the foundation for later exception flags
The project is not just about SQL, but about translating raw data into business risk signals that teams can act on quickly
Business understanding gained

This project helped me think more clearly about how operational and financial issues can be turned into automated monitoring logic. Instead of manually checking rows, the goal is to automatically identify which orders need attention and make those risks visible through dashboards, workflows, and AI-generated summaries.




Project Findings Info
Step 3: Exception Flags

In this step, I turned raw business calculations into actionable exception logic.

After creating margin_value, margin_pct, and delay_days, I added rule-based flags to identify orders that need attention:

negative_margin_flag = loss-making orders
low_margin_flag = profitable but weak-margin orders
late_shipment_flag = orders delivered after the promised date
critical_delay_flag = orders delayed by 3 or more days

I also created a priority_level column to classify each order into:

High = negative margin or critical delay
Medium = low margin or late shipment
Low = no major exception
What I learned
In BigQuery, calculated aliases cannot be safely reused inside later expressions in the same SELECT, so using a CTE makes the query cleaner and easier to maintain
Exception flags are the step where a dataset becomes operationally useful, because calculations are converted into business rules teams can act on
Separating High, Medium, and Low priority makes the output much easier for dashboards, alerts, and later AI summaries




Step 5: Reusable BigQuery Views

In this step, I moved from one-off SQL queries to reusable BigQuery views by creating vw_order_health and vw_exceptions. This made the project more structured and closer to a real analytics workflow, where business logic is saved once and reused across dashboards, alerts, and later AI-driven summaries.

What I learned
A working query is useful for testing, but reusable views make the project more scalable and professional
vw_order_health stores the full business logic for all orders
vw_exceptions creates a clean action layer with only flagged orders
Separating the full health view from the exception view improves readability, reuse, and maintenance
Business understanding gained





Step: Fixing vw_exceptions for dashboard sorting and time analysis
What went wrong

While using vw_exceptions in Looker Studio, I noticed two problems:

Priority Level was not sorting in the business order I wanted
Looker Studio was treating priority_level as plain text, so the chart sorting was inconsistent and did not naturally show Low → Medium → High.
The time chart was not clean enough for monthly analysis
Using the raw order_date field made the chart harder to read, especially because the data only covered a few months.

A second SQL issue behind the scenes was that I could not directly reuse priority_level in the same SELECT where it was first created, because of how BigQuery handles aliases.

How I fixed it

To solve this properly, I updated the vw_exceptions view by adding one more outer layer of logic:

created a separate prioritized CTE to define priority_level first
added priority_sort_order so the dashboard could sort priorities in the required business order
added priority_display as a more dashboard-friendly label
added order_month using DATE_TRUNC(order_date, MONTH) for cleaner monthly trend reporting
What I learned
Sometimes dashboard problems are not really dashboard problems, they are data model problems
It is often better to fix sorting and display logic in BigQuery views instead of fighting Looker Studio settings
If a field depends on another calculated field, an extra CTE / outer query improves readability and prevents alias errors
Adding small helper fields like priority_sort_order and order_month makes the reporting layer much cleaner and easier to control
Business understanding gained




*Reasoning why it is not yet a complete AI agent, but an AI-assisted automation workflow*


On the AI agent question, my honest answer is:

Right now, this is not yet a full AI agent.
It is an AI-assisted automation workflow.

Why is that:

it has a Brain component once we add the LLM summary
it has Tools, because it uses BigQuery and n8n workflow actions
but it does not yet really have Memory in the stronger agent sense
and it does not yet have much autonomous reasoning or multi-step decision-making

So if you presented it today, I would call it:

an AI-assisted exception monitoring workflow

That is still good and still relevant.

If you want it to feel much closer to an AI agent, then later we should add:

memory of previous runs
logic to compare “new exceptions vs already known exceptions”
reasoning about what to prioritise
possibly different actions based on what the LLM concludes

Then it becomes more agent-like.

So the honest positioning is:

Phase 1 = automation workflow
Phase 2 = AI-assisted workflow
Phase 3 later, if needed = more agent-like system with memory and reasoning

This step showed me that a strong analytics project is not just about calculations and flags. It also needs a reporting layer that is easy for business users to read, sort, and interpret correctly.

This step showed me how analytics projects become more valuable when the logic is turned into reusable data products instead of remaining as ad hoc queries.
